sed their encounters with American films to construct a national film culture. Drawing on extensive archival research, Serna explores the popular experience of cinemagoing from the perspective of exhibitors, cinema workers, journalists, censors, and fans, showing how Mexican audiences actively engaged with American films to identify more deeply with Mexico.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aMotion pictureszMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures, AmericanzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures, MexicanxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational characteristics, Mexican, in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822376798zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822376798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822376798.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles